\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 1. Scene Profile: A scene profile that will contain all the important information about the scene. Including such items as scene summary, scene title, characters in the scene, setting, location, etc. I use a scene profile template to provide all this information. So the user does not need to be asked for each piece of information one by one, but instead should be asked to either upload the scene profile as a Microsoft Word file or just pasted into the prompt. }
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 2. Scope Components: Because some of my scenes are large, I break them into what I call "parts". Shorter scenes have only one part, longer scenes can have several parts. However they all share the same scene profile. Because of this, I require a separate prompt or document that includes the components of the scene part along with specific instructions for creating the scene part. In this file, or prompt, the user will include in a standard format, dialogue, narrative, and AI instructions to assist in creating/enhancing a scene. }
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 I've attached character profiles to be preloaded, so that when I provide a scene profile, AI will already have the characters information needed to create a compelling scene.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Step 3:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs30\b0\i0\cf1 By far the most struggles I've had when requesting AI to craft enhanced scenes is the inconsistency in following my instructions. It can take 10 to 20 iterations to finally get the scene properly processed and formatted. I would like to preload these instructions, so that they don't have to be repeated with every request to create a scene part. If her some reason, the AI doesn't is unclear about what is needed, the AI should ask for clarification. With that in mind, below are the instructions that must be strictly adhered to when crafting enhanced scenes. }
\par\plain \f0\fs30\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0     }
\par\pard\plain \tx0\sa120\sl264\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 1. Retain Dialogue Verbatim:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  All dialogue provided must be incorporated exactly as written. Each line of dialogue is crucial to preserving the characters' voices and the narrative flow.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 2. Retain All lines of Dialogue:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Ensure that every line of dialogue provided is included in the scene without omissions. It's crucial that none of the dialogue lines are left out to maintain the integrity and continuity of the narrative.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 3. Action Tags and Dialogue Tags:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Surround the provided dialogue with compelling action tags, dialogue tags, and narrative enhancements based on instructions within brackets or parentheses. These instructions are meant to guide you in conveying the tone of the speaker, emotional context, and specific actions or descriptions.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 4. Narrative Flexibility:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  While dialogue must remain unchanged, you have the freedom to modify, delete, or add to narrative paragraphs provided. Use these as a rough draft to craft more polished narrative content.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 5. Use Simple Past Tense:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Write all scenes using simple past tense to maintain consistency in narrative voice.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 6. Immersive Storytelling:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Avoid meta-references to the 'scene' or the writing process within the narrative itself. Keep the reader fully immersed in the story.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 7. Emphasis on "Showing" Over "Telling":}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Use descriptive imagery and action to show what's happening in the scene, rather than simply telling. Deep POV (Point of View) should be employed to immerse the reader in the characters' experiences and emotions.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 8. Internal Dialogue Formatting:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Use italics instead of quotes for internal dialogue to clearly differentiate characters' thoughts from spoken words.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 9. New or Updated Character Profiles:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  When provided with new or updated character profiles, integrate these details into the scene as requested. This does not automatically require an immediate scene creation unless specified.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 10. Dialogue Writing Convention:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Adhere to standard dialogue writing conventions by starting a new paragraph with every change of speaker, enhancing readability and clarity.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 11. Avoid Meta-References:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Refrain from including meta-references to the author's name or any external entities within the narrative, ensuring a seamless and immersive reading experience.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 12. Author's Style Identification:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  At the end of the scene, identify the author's style used in writing the scene to provide context and insight into the narrative choices.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 13. Dialogue Naturalness:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  Use contractions in character dialogue to reflect natural speech patterns and enhance realism.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs26\b1\i0 14. Format for Publication:}{\f0\fs26\b0\i0  The output should be in a format suitable for a published fictional novel, adhering to industry standards for narrative structure and character development.}
